# Route Patterns

Routes define Express endpoints and wire up controllers with validation.

## Structure

```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import controller from "./{feature}.controller";
import { validation1, validation2 } from "./{feature}.validation";

const router = Router();

// GET /api/{feature}/list
router.get("/list", controller.getAll.bind(controller));

// GET /api/{feature}/one
router.get("/one", controller.getById.bind(controller));

// POST /api/{feature}/one
router.post(
  "/one",
  validation1,
  controller.create.bind(controller)
);

// PUT /api/{feature}/one
router.put(
  "/one",
  validation2,
  controller.update.bind(controller)
);

// DELETE /api/{feature}/one
router.delete("/one", controller.delete.bind(controller));

export default router;
```

## Rules

- Always `bind(controller)` when passing controller methods
- Add validation middleware before controller
- Use consistent URL patterns:
  - `/list` for collections
  - `/one` for single items (with query param `?id=`)
  - `/count` for counts
  - Custom routes: `/{status}/list` (e.g., `/living/list`)

## URL Conventions

```typescript
// ✅ Collections
router.get("/list", controller.getAll);

// ✅ Single item (query param)
router.get("/one", controller.getById);  // ?id=123

// ✅ Actions on single item
router.post("/one", validation, controller.create);
router.put("/one", validation, controller.update);  // ?id=123
router.delete("/one", controller.delete);  // ?id=123

// ✅ Filtered collections
router.get("/living/list", controller.getLiving);
router.get("/deceased/list", controller.getDeceased);

// ✅ Counts
router.get("/count", controller.getCount);
```

## Validation Middleware

```typescript
// ✅ Place validation between route and controller
router.post(
  "/one",
  createValidation,  // Validation middleware
  controller.create.bind(controller)
);
```

## Comments

Add clear comments for each route:

```typescript
// GET /api/persons - Get all persons
// GET /api/persons/one - Get person by ID
// POST /api/persons/one - Create new person
```
